# Question 4 - File Access and I/O Investigation

## Command 1
$ mkdir -p ~/CLI-Graded-Assignment/Q4
$ cd ~/CLI-Graded-Assignment/Q4

Explanation: Created the Q4 working directory and moved into it.

## Command 2
$ lsof | head
bash: lsof: command not found

Explanation: The lsof command is not installed in this sandbox, so /proc/self/fd was used instead to inspect open file descriptors.

## Command 3
$ ls -l /proc/self/fd
total 0
lrwx------ 1 coder coder 64 Jun 23 12:26 0 -> /dev/pts/0
lrwx------ 1 coder coder 64 Jun 23 12:26 1 -> /dev/pts/0
lrwx------ 1 coder coder 64 Jun 23 12:26 2 -> /dev/pts/0
lr-x------ 1 coder coder 64 Jun 23 12:26 3 -> /proc/675/fd

Explanation: Showed the open file descriptors of the current shell. 0 is standard input, 1 is standard output, and 2 is standard error, all connected to the terminal device /dev/pts/0.

## Command 4
$ echo "Linux I/O Test" > output.txt
$ cat output.txt
Linux I/O Test

Explanation: Used the > operator to redirect normal output into output.txt, then displayed the file to confirm.

## Command 5
$ ls nonexistentfile 2> error.txt
$ cat error.txt
ls: cannot access 'nonexistentfile': No such file or directory

Explanation: Used the 2> operator to redirect the error message (standard error) into error.txt instead of the screen, then displayed the captured error.

